Title:
Shredder-RS — x86_64 Polymorphic Mutation Engine (Instruction Shredding)

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- Shredder-RS is a Rust-based polymorphic mutation/obfuscation engine for x86_64 PE binaries that aims to hinder static analysis by “shredding” code at the instruction level.  
- It disassembles the original instruction stream, wraps each instruction into isolated mutation nodes, then physically shuffles those nodes into a new PE section and reconnects execution via relative JMPs to form a spaghetti-like control-flow graph.  
- The engine emphasizes context preservation by maintaining EFLAGS and volatile registers (e.g., via pushfq/popfq-style “context sandwiching”) to keep semantics intact while mutating layout and flow.  
- It automates PE modifications such as injecting a dedicated section (e.g., `.shred`) and hijacking the EntryPoint to redirect execution into the shredded graph.  
- This is primarily useful for red team tooling research, malware analysis evasion studies, and defenders/researchers evaluating disassembly robustness and CFG recovery under heavy obfuscation.  
- It’s interesting because it focuses on high-fidelity, instruction-granular fragmentation rather than simple junk insertion, stressing disassemblers and signature-based detection.

Technical Focus:
- x86_64 instruction decoding and re-encoding (iced-x86)
- Instruction-level fragmentation into per-instruction nodes
- Control-flow graph obfuscation via JMP-linked “spaghetti” layout
- PE file rewriting: section injection and EntryPoint hijacking
- Context preservation (EFLAGS/volatile registers) during mutation
- Static analysis disruption (linear sweep vs recursive traversal)

Use Cases:
- Obfuscating x86_64 Windows PE payloads for research and controlled red team simulations
- Testing disassembler/decompiler resilience and CFG reconstruction techniques
- Generating polymorphic variants to study signature brittleness and heuristic detection
- Building datasets for defensive research on obfuscation-aware analysis

